    <div class="quotetitle"><a href="https://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=40789156#p40789156" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Sekhmet</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Can we please stop affirming that black holes have &quot;singularities&quot; in them, as if we knew that is what's actually going on inside inside of them?</div><br />It's a succinct way of describing a black hole's innards without having to write an entire primer on quantum field theory (which I am utterly unqualified to do). And Hawking radiation isn't really virtual particles popping in and out of existence either, but that's the commonly presented analogy for that, too.<br /><br />If this were an academic paper instead of a fun and informative video for laypersons, I guess I'd be a lot picker about terminology. But it ain't, so I'm not. ¯\_(ツ)_/¯
    
  </div>
  <footer>
    <div class="tools-info">
      <aside class="tools">
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
      <span class="userinfo">20729 posts | registered <time class="reg-date">Aug 26, 2000</time></span>
