<li class="thin-divide-bottom comment neutral read"
  data-post-negative="-22"
  data-post-positive="6"
  data-user-vote="neutral"
  data-post-id="40789224"
  data-poster-id="822701"
  id="comment-40789224"
  
  data-user-sentiment="neutral"
  
  data-post-sentiment-totals="{&quot;agree&quot;:&quot;2&quot;,&quot;interesting&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;funny&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;addsto&quot;:&quot;1&quot;,&quot;disagree&quot;:&quot;1&quot;,&quot;inaccurate&quot;:&quot;1&quot;,&quot;pointless&quot;:&quot;6&quot;,&quot;abusive&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}">
  
  <header class="byline">
    <div class="author-rank">
      <span class="author" data-post-author="The Lurker Beneath">
        <a href="/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&u=822701" rel="nofollow">The Lurker Beneath</a>
        <span class="rank">Ars Centurion</span>
      </span>
      
    </div>
    <aside class="icons">
      
        <a href="?comments=1&amp;post=40789224&amp;mode=quote#reply" class='quotelink icon' rel='nofollow' title="Reply">reply</a>
      
      <a href="http://arstechnica.com/science/2022/03/exploring-the-counterintuitive-mysteries-of-black-holes-with-paul-sutter/?comments=1&post=40789224#comment-40789224" title="2022-03-30T14:23:08+00:00" rel="nofollow" class="timeago datetime">Wed Mar 30, 2022 9:23 am</a>
      <ul class="comment-tags-list">
      
      </ul>
    </aside>
  </header>
  <div class="body">
    <div class="quotetitle"><a href="https://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=40789188#p40789188" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Fatesrider</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="https://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=40789156#p40789156" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Sekhmet</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Can we please stop affirming that black holes have &quot;singularities&quot; in them, as if we knew that is what's actually going on inside inside of them?</div><br />Define a what a singularity is.<br /><br />Because I don't think you understand what that means.<br /><br />It's simple a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gravitational_singularity" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">point in space time where none of the rules of known physics apply anymore</a>.<br /><br />It's not that we know what's going on inside at all.  A singularity defies known physics.<br /><br />Trying to understand what goes on inside a black hole is the whole purpose of studying them.  And like light, they don't give up their secrets easily.  We can determine mass, spin, rotation, whether it's eating, or not, and a host of other things that we see impacting the universe.  But what's going on inside is still very much a cypher with regard to actual knowledge.  Theories are about all we have, and few of them have proven to be even remotely definitive.<br /><br />Calling it a singularity is the physics way of saying the same things cartographers used to mean by marking the edges of maps with &quot;here be dragons&quot;, because they simply didn't know what lay beyond the borders.  The same applies in physics to what lies beyond the event horizon of a black hole.<br /><br />Calling them singularities is better than calling them Domains of Space Dragons.</div><br /><br /><br />It's a theoretical point in space described by a mathematical/physical model that isn't working any more, unless infinities are real.  So saying &quot;the singularity exists&quot; isn't correct; you should say &quot;the model we are using is definitely wrong at this predicted point.&quot;  [Of course in the case of the black hole central singularity it may be wrong long before that point.]
    
  </div>
  <footer>
    <div class="tools-info">
      <aside class="tools">
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
