  <div class="body">
    <div class="quotetitle"><a href="https://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=40789594#p40789594" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">dwrd</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Those features are defined relative to the rotation of the object. Since angular momentum is conserved, we believe most black holes rotate, and therefore there will be an axis of rotation, and you can define the equator relative to that. From there, North and South are defined by convention (the &quot;right hand rule&quot;).</div><br />This is exactly correct, yes. Additionally, <strike>many</strike> some black holes emit <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Astrophysical_jet" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">jets of ionized matter</a> along their axes of rotation.
    
