      <a href="http://arstechnica.com/science/2022/03/exploring-the-counterintuitive-mysteries-of-black-holes-with-paul-sutter/?comments=1&post=40789633#comment-40789633" title="2022-03-30T16:21:05+00:00" rel="nofollow" class="timeago datetime">Wed Mar 30, 2022 11:21 am</a>
      <ul class="comment-tags-list">
      
      </ul>
    </aside>
  </header>
  <div class="body">
    I would assume that even a static black hole that was sitting in a gas or dust field would eventually develop an accretion disk based on the dynamics of the original field, and would subsequently start rotating itself in the same direction.
    
  </div>
  <footer>
    <div class="tools-info">
      <aside class="tools">
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
      <span class="userinfo">1684 posts | registered <time class="reg-date">Jun 20, 2020</time></span>
    </div>
  </footer>
</li>

<li class="thin-divide-bottom comment neutral read"
  data-post-negative="-2"
  data-post-positive="5"
  data-user-vote="neutral"
  data-post-id="40789642"
  data-poster-id="6291"
  id="comment-40789642"
  
  data-user-sentiment="neutral"
  
  data-post-sentiment-totals="{&quot;agree&quot;:&quot;1&quot;,&quot;interesting&quot;:&quot;1&quot;,&quot;funny&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;addsto&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;disagree&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;inaccurate&quot;:&quot;1&quot;,&quot;pointless&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;abusive&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}">
  
  <header class="byline">
    <div class="author-rank">
      <span class="author" data-post-author="Xepherys">
        <a href="/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&u=6291" rel="nofollow">Xepherys</a>
        <span class="rank">Ars Praetorian</span>
      </span>
      <a class="subscriber" href="/store/product/subscriptions/">et Subscriptor</a>
    </div>
    <aside class="icons">
      
        <a href="?comments=1&amp;post=40789642&amp;mode=quote#reply" class='quotelink icon' rel='nofollow' title="Reply">reply</a>
      
      <a href="http://arstechnica.com/science/2022/03/exploring-the-counterintuitive-mysteries-of-black-holes-with-paul-sutter/?comments=1&post=40789642#comment-40789642" title="2022-03-30T16:23:03+00:00" rel="nofollow" class="timeago datetime">Wed Mar 30, 2022 11:23 am</a>
      <ul class="comment-tags-list">
      
      </ul>
    </aside>
  </header>
  <div class="body">
    I don't really understand why we assume it runs afoul of our understanding of quantum physics, or physics generally.  I get that we have no way, currently, of retrieving information from a black hole (though it isn't as if we've tried in any practical fashion, either, so... there's that), but fundamentally changing information as it becomes &quot;part of&quot; the black hole seems in line with our general theories.<br /><br />For instance, we know that mass can be converted into energy, but if you capture the resulting energy there isn't always a means to understand what it was before.  In some cases we can make educated guesses, based on the type of energy, but fundamentally that's just an aspect of entropy.  We can't take the heat and radiation from a nuclear explosion and turn it back into a bomb.<br /><br />It seems to me that a black hole's consumption of information is just a part of an entropic system.
    
  </div>
  <footer>
    <div class="tools-info">
