  <div class="body">
    <div class="quotetitle"><a href="https://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=40789594#p40789594" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">dwrd</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="https://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=40789554#p40789554" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">BatCrapCrazy</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">So lady physicist ( forgot her name) says that black holes have accretion discs, so that means that a black must have a well defined equator and with that a north and south. somehow sounds strange to me.</div><br /><br />Those features are defined relative to the rotation of the object. Since angular momentum is conserved, we believe most black holes rotate, and therefore there will be an axis of rotation, and you can define the equator relative to that. From there, North and South are defined by convention (the &quot;right hand rule&quot;).</div><br /><br />Thanks for the explanation! Seems everywhere they portray all black holes as rotating, but i wonder how a non rotating black hole would be illustrated.
    
  </div>
