    <aside class="icons">
      
        <a href="?comments=1&amp;post=40789886&amp;mode=quote#reply" class='quotelink icon' rel='nofollow' title="Reply">reply</a>
      
      <a href="http://arstechnica.com/science/2022/03/exploring-the-counterintuitive-mysteries-of-black-holes-with-paul-sutter/?comments=1&post=40789886#comment-40789886" title="2022-03-30T17:26:57+00:00" rel="nofollow" class="timeago datetime">Wed Mar 30, 2022 12:26 pm</a>
      <ul class="comment-tags-list">
      
      </ul>
    </aside>
  </header>
  <div class="body">
    One of things that trouble me about black holes is that I would have thought that matter at the level of a proton or neutron would be incompressible. Do physicists have any kind of theory on the compressibility of matter?<br /><br />Take a neutron star, for instance. Let's say you start lobbing additional matter at it. Eventually it will collapse into a black hole, but does that happen all of a sudden (poof!) or does it crumple up slowly? Can matter be partially compressed, or is it all or nothing? Do physicists even bother with these issues?
    
  </div>
  <footer>
